<br>
By The NuclearSpace.com Team.<br>
<br>
There was a time once when we were all about exploration, conquest and colonization - we can now be defined as a civilization that focuses on internal problems that will or can never be completely solved. <br>
<br>
A cold shudder or chill may go up your spine looking at old black and white photographs of people, events, machines, inventions, proposals and visionary schemes from the early part of the last century. <br>
<br>
To see what could have and should have been is sobering to say the least. That generation of yesteryear believed so firmly in science, technology and the progress of Western Man in all areas of life, that it is easy to see why they have been called 'The Greatest Generation'. They believed that science (understanding) and technology (application) would lead to a higher standard of living, which it did. They believed in letting technology solve its own problems. They believed in grand projects of engineering.<br>
<br>
So where did we go wrong and why did we change?<br>
<br>
Prometheus was the Titan who in ancient Greek mythology stole fire from the Gods and then gave it to humankind. It is also the rather apt title given to the propulsion side of Nasa's latest Nuclear Space Initiative. To primitive man, fire was the most fearful elemental force in the World. All beasts ran before it and sparked by lightning it would rapidly engulf entire forests. Wild animals have a built in primeval fear of fire and just the smell of burning is enough to trigger their flight reflex. Early man would have held the same deeply ingrained respect for this ancient natural enemy. There must have been a time, tens of thousands of years ago, when early humans began to realise they could gain mastery over this terror. We can imagine a tribal gathering arguing the pro's and con's of experimenting with such a deadly killer. Of opening that Pandora's box. No doubt it was a difficult decision and one fraught with powerful arguments on both sides. <br>
<br>
&quot;It is taboo to make fire. You will kill us all.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;We can heat our homes in winter and cook our food.&quot;<br>
<br>
We all know the result. Progress won out in the end. There were certainly disasters along the way but more was gained than lost from harnessing fire. Nobody would ever suggest that we made the wrong decision and should consider returning to the stone age. Don't laugh. That first accidental discovery of what happens when two sticks are rubbed together in a certain way might easily have been buried by frightened elders in some long ago forgotten era. It's full possibilities might never have been realised. <br>
<br>
Technology that is banned by any nation invariably comes back to bite it in the rear. The British virtually outlawed cars at the turn of the century in favour of hoofs. The British Car industry has never really caught up with Europe or the US as a consequence. Again, the British Naval Admiralty saw no value in submarines. Much to the glee of German U-boat Commanders decades later on. If the Chinese had looked just a little more closely at the possibilities of their fireworks, those entertaining sky shows which so lit up the eyes of their children, they would not have been so surprised in another era by the oncoming Western forces carrying repeater rifles. Instead of western powers dominating recent world history it might have been Asia instead. The Mayans had toys with wheels but never built carts. Even the ancient greek inventor Heron who designed and built the first primitive steam engine, failed to realise the import of his device. Despite an appreciation of the possibilities presented by levers, he failed to see his spinning steam contraption as anything more than a toy. If he had taken only half a step further he would have become the father of an ancient industrial revolution over two thousand years ago. Where might we be today if he had? <br>
<br>
Opposition movements to nuclear power in space are fond of fearmongering campaigns. Often associated with conspiracy theorists and anti-technologists, their arguments fall into two shallow categories. Gutter science which is easily disproved or simply accusing others of lying.<br>
<br>
Here are some examples from the Global Network Against Weapons And Nuclear Power In Space.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;In 1997 NASA launched the Cassini space probe carrying 72 pounds of plutonium that fortunately did not experience failure. If it had, hundreds of thousands of people around the world could have been contaminated.&quot;<br>
<br>
How can you cite a success as a failure? This is just 'spin doctoring'. Hundreds of thousands contaminated they say. What is the risk mitigation source for that statement? The actual available evidence indicates that a worstcase scenario would be unlikely to cause a single fatality. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;Beyond accidents impacting the planet, the space nuclear production process at the DoE labs will lead to significant numbers of workers and communities being contaminated.&quot; <br>
<br>
Beer is 13 times more radioactive than the cooling water discharged from a nuclear power plant. We are contaminated every time we walk out into the sun. By not giving contamination levels it is an empty statement to say people will be contaminated. The number one source of man made radiation released into the environment is from X-ray diagnostics. Far outstripping fallout, Chernobyl, office equipment and all others combined. Shall we ban hospitals then? Safety regulations administering the operation of nuclear plants are already excessively stringent. If the White House was a nuclear power plant it would probably be closed down due to the 'excessive' radioactivity in it's walls. They are known to contain naturally occuring Uranium. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;...the NASA space nukes initiative represents the Bush administration's covert move to develop power systems for space-based weapons such as lasers on satellites. The military has often stated that their planned lasers in space will require enormous power projection capability and that nuclear reactors in orbit...&quot; <br>
<br>
The military abandoned it's nuclear space reactor (SP-100) in the 80's. This information of theirs is simply 20 years out of date. The military's space based reactor research is covert and secretive out of reasons of national security. It was in the news frequently during the mid to late 80's. It would be wrong of the military not to investigate the possibilities of space and I would have thought only a foreign power would support restricting such endeavours. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;NASA's nuclear rocket is a Trojan horse for the militarization of space.&quot;<br>
<br>
Technically it's assumed to be a reactor powered ion engine, not a nuclear rocket. NASA is a civilian agency and differentiated from the military. Ofcourse, the militarisation of space is eventually going to happen. The Air Force routinely flies aircraft at the edge of space. The prospect of others using space as a weapons launchpad is sufficient reason to expect a key role in future. In today's insecure terrorist plagued World it seems sensible to protect our space interests such as communication satellites.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;In the end hundreds and hundreds of billions of dollars will be wasted on plans for the nuclearization and weaponization of space.&quot;<br>
<br>
How does he know this? Can the author provide a budget line item that has these figures? No. Because it's a flawed statement, an 'assumption'. Perhaps a quote on the market value of one moderate sized iron ore asteroid would fit in here rather nicely? Eros is estimated to be worth around 40 trillion dollars US in valuable resources including Platinum. It's true that Nasa has a zero profit policy but they will be opening the frontier for others by showing the way. The wealth which could be ultimately generated is incalculable. Tourism, resources, energy production etc.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;Their plans now literally threaten the life of the entire planetary ecosystem.&quot;<br>
<br>
Doomsday scare tactics with no real science to back up the claim. Hundreds of high megaton nuclear bomb tests from the 50's and 60's released tons of Plutonium and highly enriched Uranium directly into the atmosphere and I would like to point out how the Earth did NOT become a wasteland as a result. The last launch of Plutonium by Nasa was Cassini back in 97 and the possibility of a launch failure was well planned for. The fuel was so well encased it would likely have been picked up and reused in a later mission if an unlikely accident had occured. The next planned Plutonium launch is for this Summer and it will carry 16 penny sized pellets of Plutonium for the twin Mars Rovers. Again, every precaution is being taken. It is ridiculous to hype up this miniscule risk when coal burning plants routinely churn out thousands of tons of Uranium and Thorium into the environment. Radioactive elements commonly found in coal beds and burned up with the coal before being pumped straight into our atmosphere. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;Ultimately NASA envisions mining colonies on the Moon, Mars, and asteroids that would be powered by nuclear reactors.&quot;<br>
<br>
This has never been NASA's goal. As a non-profit organisation they are largely restricted to exploration.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;All of the above missions would be launched from the Kennedy Space Center in Florida on rockets with a historic 10% failure rate. &quot; <br>
<br>
This is simply ignorant rhetoric. I believe the shuttle's failure rate is about 1 failure for every 200 launches. A failure does not automatically mean a big fireball on the pad or en-route. Most failures are simply cancellations.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;In April, 1964 a U.S. military satellite with 2.1 pounds of plutonium-238 on-board fell back to Earth and burned up as it hit the atmosphere spreading the toxic plutonium globally as dust to be ingested by the people of the planet.&quot;<br>
<br>
The SNAP-9A RTG was an old 1960's design. The redesigned RTG's that launched after this have proven their safety with no release of radioactive elements despite two instances of catastrophic rocket failure. The newer designs have PROVED that they are safe even under the most extreme abuse. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;In order to fund these missions Bush and Congress will have to cut programs like social security, education, health care, child care, public transit and environmental protection. &quot;<br>
<br>
We should only spend money on social programs right. If any leader spouts this nonsense, you know it's close to election time. It's the tired old arguement of 'Why do we spend money on space when people are starving down here on earth?' Those against science and progress like to bring this question up repeatedly. The ancestors of these individuals were probably the same cave dwellers who spoke against messing with fire. &quot;It's a waste of time. It will never lead anywhere. Forget about it. There are more important things to do like picking berries from bushes and fleas from our scalps.&quot;<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;During the 1950s and 1960s NASA spent over $10 billion to build the nuclear rocket program which was cancelled in the end because of the fear that a launch accident would contaminate major portions of Florida and beyond.&quot;<br>
<br>
This is completely untrue. It was actually cancelled because Americans lost interest in a Mars Mission. Mr Gagnon is giving his fellow protestors an undeserved pat on the back here. Nuclear thermal rockets quietly faded away with our enthusiasm for space.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;NASA hasn't learned its lesson from its history involving space nuclear power,&quot; says Micho Kaku, &quot;and a hallmark of science is that you learn from previous mistakes. NASA doggedly pursues its fantasy of nuclear power in space.&quot;<br>
<br>
Fantasy of nuclear power in space? A large number of deep space probes and satellites already use nuclear RTG's. Our sun is a giant nuclear bomb. Nuclear power is already firmly entrenched in space. The only mistake made was cancelling the reactor programs. Nuclear power is the only sensible option for serious space missions. That's why we are now finally returning to it. The biggest fantasy being doggedly pursued is the one Michio Kaku preaches. That solar power can do the job for us instead. This is a most impractical suggestion for missions to the outer reaches of the solar system where light is thousands of times dimmer.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;NASA, DoE, and the Pentagon are not asking the tax paying public if we want to suffer the risk and costs of nuclear power in space.&quot;<br>
<br>
I would welcome a public opinion poll asking this very question. There was one at Space.com a couple of years ago as I recall. It had the largest response in the history of the site. Well over 95% approval for a nuclear space initiative. Bruce Gagnon has always claimed to speak for the masses but I have yet to see any evidence in support of this assumption.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;NASA says that poses a 1-in-1,030 possibility of a radioactive accident near the launch site and, even in the worst-case scenario, the most exposed individuals would be subjected to less radiation than a single medical X-ray. &quot;<br>
&quot;NASA is lying,&quot; said Bruce Gagnon.<br>
<br>
No explanation or facts to back up his opinion... just simply, &quot;NASA is lying&quot;. <br>
 <br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.space.com/images/h_darthnuke_03.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
For the third year in a row GNAWANPIS (Global Network Against Weapons And Nuclear Power In Space) will be disrupting the annual symposium on Space Nuclear Power &amp; Propulsion. Situated in Albuquerque, New Mexico and slated for February 3-4, 2003 . They'll be waving placards, trying to get their faces in front of the TV camera's and pestering school children who have travelled a long way to learn about careers in this high tech industry.<br>
 <br>
We of NuclearSpace.com hope to see a strong gathering of protestors peacefully rallying against the Global Network's own small protest. <br>
<br>
Although the dangers of nuclear power have been outragiously exagerrated by our opposition, we at the Pro-Nuclear Space Movement don't deny that some element of risk does indeed exist. A degree of risk is always involved when any technology is exploited. Our organisation formed in response to decades of fearmongering from fringe movements we felt required a response and while enthusiastic about the future of nuclear power in space we would be remiss in our duty of promoting informed debate if we were to deny any danger existed. Neither we nor Nasa have ever stated such a denial of risk despite claims by GNAWANPIS to the contrary. We both simply believe those risks on balance to be acceptable ones. If a technology that has any potential threat associated with it must be banned, then we should start with automobiles. Thousands of people die each year as a direct result of cars. <br>
<br>
Prometheus of Greek myth ended up very badly. Paying a high price for his having helped humanity. Mythical tales seem to have a recurring theme of tragedy built into them. Perhaps because people of long ago already recognised that nothing worthwhile is ever gained without pain or sacrifice. We have already paid the cost of developing nuclear power over the last half a century. Our experience with the most compact source of energy available has paid off. To now throw that hard won technology away and with it the possibilities for nuclear power in space would be shortsighted.<br>
<br>
Perhaps one of the best arguements for allowing nuclear power to increase our foothold in space is provided by Daniel Durda, a senior research scientist at the Southwest Research Institute in Boulder, Colorado.<br>
<br>
&quot;The worst scenario I can think of is a multi-kilometer-diameter, long-period comet discovered several months out on an impact trajectory as it is entering the inner solar system,&quot; he said. &quot;There is absolutely nothing we could do about it at this point in time. Nothing.&quot; <br>
<br>
So let's start a poll and see where space enthusiasts presently stand on nuclear power in space.<br>
